@node Introduction

   First of all, I'm sorry for the poor english in this guide, but after all
this isn't my native language.

   Tagger is an external utility to use with any @{" MMS " link MMS} like 
April or Foozle from Peer Hasselmeyer. It's useful to add funny sentences 
and put some humor into your messages.

 Taglines are supported by many Off-Line readers, however, most known
FTS-1 Fido MMS lack this feature. Well, cry no more, Tagger is here!
Tagger is now in version 2.01 containing several improvements that turn 
this program into the most powerful of his kind.

 This software is fully userfriendly and takes advantage of the superb new
libraries and system calls. It has been tested in machines like the  A500+, A600
A1200, A3000 and A4000 , and seems Enforcer Hit free. However, if you find
any "guru requester", feel free to contact me and report the problem.

 This program is under the concept of Shareware and if you like it, and you
think that it's worth to use, I must ask you to @{" register " link Registration} it.


@endnode

@node MMS

  MMS - Stands for Mail Manipulation System , programs that are used to
process messages from a Message NetWork.
  With these programs you can process messages in a Off-Line way.

@endnode

@node Installation

The  easiest  way  to  use  Tagger is to @{" invoke " link Invoke}  him from
a AmigaDOS script file that calls both your favorite text editor and Tagger
himself. A @{" demo script " link "Demo Script"} is provided with this pack 
and you can modify it to your needs and use it with your software.

 Taking Foozle for an example, run FZI (Foozle's configuration program) and
press the "General 1" gadget. When you get to the editor preferences
write something like "execute Fido:Foozle/Editor %" where "Editor" is
your script file.

@endnode

@node "Demo Script"

   Here's a detailed description from a script file:

               ------------------//-------------------

.key opt1
.bra {
.ket }

Fido:Remap2 -a {opt1}                   ;Remap message to the Amiga standard

Work:Tools/CygnusEd/CED {opt1} -KeepIO  ;Call your favorite text Editor here

Fido:Tagger/Tagger {opt1}               ;Invoke Tagger!!

Fido:Remap2 -i {opt1}                   ;Remap message to the IBM standard


               ------------------//-------------------

The Remap2 utility is not provided with this pack. You can FREQ REMAP2.LHA
from Node 2:361/9 or use any other text file converter available.


@endnode


@node Invoke

  USAGE: Tagger [<File_to_tag> [<TagList_File> [<Editor_File>] ] ]


 You can call tagger both from CLI or WorkBench2.xx

 When you Invoke Tagger a configuration file is Loaded from ENVARC:
containing several information about the way you want tagger to work,
this configuration contains

             - Last Tagline used
             - Last File Tagged
             - Last @{" TagLine Library " link Library} file used
             - Editor Calling String Configuration

 If you don't pass any arguments to Tagger and the configuration file
contains @{" INVALID " link Invalid} Information, them Tagger will prompt you a
File Requester to ask for Valid Information.

WARNING:  You can't Cancel this requester. Because of the way Tagger works, it 
           will ask you again for some valid information.

@endnode

@node Library

 Tagger TagLine files are plain vanilla text files containg your favorite
sentences. The default file extension for TagLine files is ".TAGS" , however you
can import any kind of text file from any system or package.

 This pack contains a TagLine file called "TagLinesBank.TAGS" containing more
than 1000 taglines ready to use.



*** WARNING ***

 This is an UNREGISTERED version of Tagger. There is a limitation of 55
characters per TagLine. If you decide to @{" register " link Registration}, there will be sent to you
a fully functional version without any kind of limitations.


@endnode

@node Invalid

 Invalid information for Version 2.01 , are Non-existing filenames.

 When, for any reason tagger can't open a file, it will prompt you a File
Requester to ask for the proper information so that it runs properly.
@endnode

@node Using

                           USING TAGGER

 The @{" First Time " link First} you use Tagger, it will ask you for some information

 Once invoked, Tagger shows you a full size window with a list of TagLines
for you to chose. You can chose a TagLine by Double-Clicking one or Clicking
one and pressing the OK gadget.

 If you wish to use another TagLine file, just press the Requester Gadget and
select another TagLine File. You can also edit the selected TagLine or the
entire TagLine File by clicking the respective gadgets.

 If you Forgot to mention something in your message, the click the EDIT MESSAGE
gadget to recall the Text Editor.

 If you prefer to leave your message without a TagLine, just press the CANCEL
gadget and move on.



@endnode

@node First

 When you Run Tagger for the first Time, it doesn't knows exactly what to
do, so it will prompt you a File Requester and ask for some Information
so that it can fill a configuration file.

 The First thing it will ask, is a "TagLines File". Just give it the
file named TagLinesBank.TAGS that can be found in this pack. Tagger is
now ready to run.

 Now select the "Open" option in the menus and select the file that will be
Tagged. 
 Now select the "Editor" option in the menus and select your favorite Text
Editor that will be used to edit your TagLines and to Re-Edit your messages. 

WARNING:  You can't Cancel this requester. Because of the way Tagger works, it 
           will ask you again for some valid information.

@endnode


